# Prose style

Write in plain, simple sentences. Avoid punctuation that packs multiple ideas into one line.

## Do

- Use short sentences. One idea per sentence when possible.
- Split compound thoughts with periods, commas, or bullet lists.
- Use "and", "but", or "so" to connect related ideas when a single sentence still reads clearly.

## Don't

- **Em-dashes (—)**. Rephrase or use a period instead.
- **Semicolons**. Use two sentences, or rewrite with "and" / a comma where it stays grammatical.

## Examples

```markdown
❌ The firewall blocks the IP — rate limits still apply for other clients.
✅ The firewall blocks the IP. Rate limits still apply for other clients.

❌ Update the schema; restart mothership to pick up the migration.
✅ Update the schema. Restart mothership to pick up the migration.

❌ This works for IPv4; IPv6 needs a separate check.
✅ This works for IPv4. IPv6 needs a separate check.
```

Applies to chat replies, commit messages, PR text, and user-facing docs unless code or identifiers require exact punctuation.
